1. Goal of Network Security in OpenShift
The main goal is:
Protect network traffic between applications inside and outside the cluster
Two main concerns:
1️⃣ External traffic security
Users accessing apps from internet.
2️⃣ Internal traffic security
Pods communicating inside the cluster.
Example architecture:
User (Internet)
      │
      ▼
Router / Ingress
      │
      ▼
Service
      │
      ▼
Pods
TLS ensures:
Encrypted communication
Authentication
Data integrity
________________________________________
2. Accessing Applications from External Networks
Applications running inside OpenShift are normally private.
To expose them externally we use:
Method	Description
NodePort	exposes service on node port
LoadBalancer	cloud load balancer
Ingress	Kubernetes ingress resource
Route	OpenShift native external access
Most common in OpenShift:
Route
________________________________________
3. What is an OpenShift Route?
A Route exposes an application to external users using a public hostname.
Example:
https://api.apps.example.com
Route components:
Client
   │
   ▼
Router
   │
   ▼
Service
   │
   ▼
Pods
Command to create route:
oc expose service myapp
Example:
oc expose service httpd
Result:
http://httpd-myproject.apps.cluster.com
________________________________________
4. Role of the Router
OpenShift uses a router (HAProxy) managed by the Ingress Operator.
Router responsibilities:
Accept external requests
Match hostname
Forward traffic to correct service
Router typically runs in namespace:
openshift-ingress
Check router pods:
oc get pods -n openshift-ingress
________________________________________
5. Unencrypted Routes
Basic route example:
HTTP
Command:
oc expose service httpd
Traffic flow:
Client ---- HTTP ---- Router ---- HTTP ---- Pod
Problem:
traffic not encrypted
This is not secure for production.
________________________________________
6. TLS Encryption
TLS = Transport Layer Security
TLS provides:
Feature	Description
Encryption	protects data
Authentication	verifies identity
Integrity	prevents tampering
Example:
HTTPS
Instead of:
http://app.example.com
We use:
https://app.example.com
________________________________________
7. TLS Termination Types in OpenShift Routes
OpenShift supports 3 TLS termination modes.
Mode	Encryption Location
Edge	Router only
Passthrough	Application
Re-encrypt	Router + Application
________________________________________
8. Edge Termination
Edge termination means:
TLS terminates at the router
Architecture:
Client --- HTTPS ---> Router --- HTTP ---> Pod
Encryption path:
Client → Router = encrypted
Router → Pod = NOT encrypted
Advantages:
Simple
Router manages certificate
Most commonly used
Disadvantage:
internal traffic unencrypted
________________________________________
Creating Edge Route
Command:
oc create route edge \
--service api-frontend \
--hostname api.apps.acme.com \
--key api.key \
--cert api.crt
Explanation:
Option	Meaning
route edge	create edge TLS route
--service	backend service
--hostname	public hostname
--key	TLS private key
--cert	TLS certificate
________________________________________
Example Flow
Browser
   │ HTTPS
   ▼
Router
   │ HTTP
   ▼
Service
   ▼
Pod
________________________________________
9. Default Router Certificates
If you do not provide certificates, OpenShift uses internal certificate authority (CA).
Command to check:
oc get secret router-ca \
-n openshift-ingress-operator -o yaml
These certificates are self-signed.
Browsers might show warning:
Not trusted certificate
________________________________________
10. Passthrough Termination
Passthrough means:
Router does NOT terminate TLS
Architecture:
Client --- HTTPS ---> Router --- HTTPS ---> Pod
Encryption path:
Client → Pod = fully encrypted
Router only passes traffic.
Advantages:
End-to-end encryption
Application controls TLS
Supports mutual TLS
Disadvantages:
Router cannot inspect traffic
More complex configuration
________________________________________
Requirements
Application must provide:
TLS certificate
TLS private key
HTTPS server
These certificates are usually stored in:
OpenShift Secrets
________________________________________
TLS Secret Example
Create secret:
oc create secret tls mycert \
--cert=tls.crt \
--key=tls.key
Mount secret inside pod:
/etc/tls/
Application then loads certificate.
________________________________________
11. Re-encrypt Termination
Re-encrypt provides full encryption across the entire path.
Architecture:
Client --- HTTPS ---> Router --- HTTPS ---> Pod
But router:
terminates TLS
then re-encrypts it
So two TLS sessions exist.
Client → Router
Router → Pod
Certificates:
Connection	Certificate
Client → Router	external certificate
Router → Pod	internal service certificate
________________________________________
Example Flow
Browser
   │ HTTPS (cert: myapp.com)
   ▼
Router
   │ HTTPS (cert: service.namespace.svc)
   ▼
Service
   ▼
Pod
________________________________________
12. Service Certificates (service-ca)
OpenShift includes service-ca controller.
Purpose:
Automatically generate TLS certificates for services
Example internal hostname:
my-app.namespace.svc.cluster.local
Service CA generates:
certificate
private key
secret
Pod mounts secret and uses certificate.
________________________________________
13. Comparing TLS Termination Types
Feature	Edge	Passthrough	Re-encrypt
Router terminates TLS	Yes	No	Yes
App handles TLS	No	Yes	Yes
End-to-end encryption	No	Yes	Yes
Complexity	Low	Medium	High
Common usage	Most common	Special cases	Secure production
________________________________________
14. Example Route Commands
Create simple route:
oc expose service myapp
Create edge route:
oc create route edge --service=myapp
Create passthrough route:
oc create route passthrough --service=myapp
Create reencrypt route:
oc create route reencrypt --service=myapp
________________________________________
15. View Routes
List routes:
oc get routes
Example output:
NAME     HOST/PORT                PATH
httpd    httpd.apps.cluster.com
Describe route:
oc describe route httpd
